snippet.title: Best tech cars
snippet.description: The following cars represent the most technically advanced available.

snippet.title: 2015 BMW X4
snippet.description: The new X4 from BMW debuted at the 2014 New York auto show,with a design that defies convention.

snippet.title: 2015 BMW M4 Convertible
snippet.description: At the New York auto show, BMW presented the all-new M4 with a retractable hard top.

snippet.title: 2014 BMW 428i
snippet.description: When optioned well, the 2014 BMW 428i achieves an excellent balance between being an exciting sports car and an everyday driver with modern, connected tech, and it looks good doing it.

snippet.title: 2015 BMW M4
snippet.description: What may seem like a simple name change, from M3 coupe to M4, actually covers a whole new car, with high-tech performance components that should make it a master of the track.

snippet.title: 2015 BMW 435i Gran Coupe
snippet.description: By adding two doors to the 4 Series Coupe, BMW may have built a better 3 Series. But is this Gran Coupe really necessary?

snippet.title: 2013 BMW 320i sedan
snippet.description: The 2013 BMW 320i is a more accessible 3 Series, with driving dynamics similar to its more powerful siblings. However, techies will want to look further up the line for gadgets.

snippet.title: 2015 BMW i8
snippet.description: Using an advanced plug-in hybrid drivetrain and carbon fiber construction, the BMW i8 looks like the start of a new era for automobiles.

snippet.title: 2014 BMW 435i
snippet.description: In recent years, some of the performance shine has come off the BMW 3 Series. Fortunately, the 4 Series is here to pick up the slack.

snippet.title: 2014 BMW M6 Gran Coupe
snippet.description: The 2014 BMW M6 Gran Coupe requires real skill to enjoy the extent of its capabilities, but its performance is exhilarating, while advanced cabin electronics help the driver under more sedate driving conditions.
